ar   2 ‘bear’."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David De Blare of that Ilk, 4th Lord of Blair was born about 1230, in Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, William De Blare of that Ilk, 3rd Lord of Blair, was 52 and his mother, Eleanor, was 26. He had at least 1 son. He was buried in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1230–":"umbes 1230–Surnud","1225–1296":"1225–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1290–1370":"1290–1370","1180–1232":"1180–1232","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1370":"1370","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Ayrshire, Kingdom of Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayr Striling, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1230–":"noin 1230–Kuollut","1225–1296":"1225–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1290–1370":"1290–1370","1180–1232":"1180–1232","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1228":"noin 1228","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1296